Genomic sequencing revealed that SARS-CoV-2 shares 96% nucleotide sequence homology with the BatCoV RaTG13 strain, which was isolated from a bat,

 Rhinolophus affinis

from China’s Yunnan Province (2013), proving the fact that bats acted as natural reservoirs (     ). Furthermore, the occurrence of Malayan pangolins (

 Manis javanica

) served as the intermediate host which was investigated by Guangdong and Guangxi customs during the anti-smuggling operations. The Pangolin-CoV genome showed an 85.5–92.4% resemblance to SARS-CoV-2. Surprisingly, RBD of Pangolin-CoV genomes have 99% amino acid identical to SARS-CoV-2. Strikingly, the Bat CoV RaTG13 and SARS-CoV-2 shared only 89.2% amino acid identity in the RBD region (     ). Till now, pangolin and bats have emerged as the only mammals identified to be highly affected by SARS-CoV-2 related SARS-CoV (     ); (     ).

